Published Publicly as 1.0.0

Added Changelog

Updated braille generator to have all shortform words recognized

Updated README to fix typos

Several feature updates to displayer:
     Recognize newline characters
     Notify the user that there is a new line
     Automatically delays for enough time for the user to actually go to the new line. 
     Speed control (measured in cells per minute) has been added and users can now control this speed themselves. Minumum speed is 10 cells per minute. If users want a slower speed, they should use manual mode. Maximum speed is 120 cells per minute, and will only be used by advanced braille users. I am open to increasing this limit by request in the future. 

    Page width is handled currently, in that reaching the right edge of the page (width defined by user) will prompt user to go to next line in both auto and manual mode. Similar to encountering the newline character. This feature will be expanded upon to warn users in advance that given their current page width, the next word is too long and they should move to next line, but that feature doesn't exist yet


1.0.2 Release

Fixed a bug leading to buttons relating to updates not being clickable

1.1.0 Release

Fixed massive oversight on update logic which gave updater permissions one level higher than intended, leading to the deletion of everything in the folder one level above the folder of this project. (Ask me how I know) This bug is completely fixed now, and the update logic has extra safeguards in place to prevent such issues.

1.1.2 Release

When in auto mode, the printed text will disappear during the short period between cell inputs if the cell inputs are identical. Example: in hello, the period between the 2 l characters will have a blank text showing, to ensure the user understands that it is 2 different instances of the letter. While I believe that the resetting and rehighlighting of the buttons was suffucuent, this adds another layer of guarantees for the ability to learn braille with this software. Please note that multicell contractions are unaffected: Example: According which is dots (6) (1), (1,4) will not flash "According" as it will stay consitently throughout the displaying of the cells making it up.

1.1.3 Release

Brought 1.1.2 change forward such that the shown enlgish characters are always removed at the same time as the short period between cell inputs begins. Now the only time that the shown characters are not removed are if the shown characters are related to several subsequent cells. Example: "Hello.." as text input will have "H" shown for the full time of the following cell inputs (6) and (1,2,5) without disappearing since the H is related to both of those cells. The H will be removed at the time the last related cell is removed. All other characters will be removed at the exact time their cell display ends.

1.2.0 Release

Page width controls now work correctly when in automatic mode, telling users to go to the next line as soon as they run out of space on their current line, as determined by the page width they selected (default 42 cells wide) Previously this feature only worked in manual mode, but it has now been made available in automatic mode, a place it is arguably far more useful. Upon reaching the end of the page, as defined by the page width value, the screen will display a message telling the user to go to the next line, similar to if a newline character was detected, and the message will appear for 3 seconds, which should be enough time for the user to reset the typehead, and roll the wheel. If this is not enough time, the user can choose to pause as well. Left and right arrow keys, typically used for manual mode, will also work in automatic mode now, a feature requested by most users, so you can skip forwards or backards while in automatic mode, if you, for instance missed a letter or an entire word you can easily return without needing to disable automatic mode, move back with left arrow keys, and then re-enable automatic mode. Fixed an odd bug relating to the display of numbers, via a recursive (in name only) function call. Numbers should display the braille dots and brailler buttons accurately now, whereas before only the print copy would be shown. With this release, most things work correctly but there are a few plans for future updates to make this tool more accurate. 
Current plans are as follows:
    Entirely capitalized words appropriately getting a double (6) modifier instead of each letter receiving a dot 6 modifier
    Early warning system for words that would overrun the page width, such that a newline occurs sooner, leading to words not being cut off at the edge of the page

1.2.1 Patch

Fixed a bug leading to crashes when using the "infinite" page width in automatic mode, by adding similar behavior as exists in manual mode. Additionally, implemenmted a None type check to avoid crashes relating to certain punctuation, formatting, or special characters found in some files which are not currently recognized in the braille dictionary generated with this project. This update should resolve many crashes.

1.2.2 Patch

Added an exit button so users can end the program without using hotkeys like Alt F4 or CMD W. The button is at the top of the screen, clearly labeled, highlighted in red, and bold compared to other buttons. Should prevent accidental clicking. Clicking the exit button will immediately exit the program. 

1.2.3 Path

Fixed a counting bug relating to how many cells had been typed since the most recently new line. This bug, could in rare circumstances cause a crash. The circumestances of this crash were very complicated and only really acheivable if trying to break the program, which is how I found it. In fixing this bug, I also fixed another bug which caused inconsistent application of newline instructions if the user went back any number of cells past where a suggested new line had popped up. That bug led to a slippage of cells versus page width, and would sometimes hide one of the cells when moving in reverse order. All of these issues have now been fixed. With this bug fix, the groundwork has been laid for the implementation of the early warning system for words longer than the amount of space remaining on the page. This feature should be added by 04/17/2026 at the latest.